  "summary": "Mrs. Ariadne Oliver speaks with Deirdre (Dilly) Henderson regarding the dog, Ben. Deirdre recognizes Mrs. Oliver and expresses admiration for her books, though she notes her mother dislikes detective stories. The conversation turns to a recent murder in a nearby cottage involving an elderly cleaning lady. Deirdre explains that the victim's tenant, James Bentley, was arrested because money was found hidden under the floorboards. Deirdre believes Bentley is innocent, describing him as a lonely man who recently lost his mother. She notes her own empathy for him because she and her mother depend on each other, whereas she has a difficult relationship with her \"heartless\" stepfather, Mr. Weatherby. After Deirdre leaves for Hunter Manor, Mrs. Oliver writes in her notebook that Deirdre is not the killer.\n\nWhile walking toward the Long Grass Hotel, Mrs. Oliver encounters Robin Upward and Eve Carpenter, whose husband is a future Member of Parliament. Robin jokingly suggests that Mrs. Oliver's next murder scene should be set in Broadhurst Gardens and discusses fictional murder plots involving himself or Eve. Robin also mentions that Eve intends to invite Hercule Poirot to a dinner party at her home. During this encounter, they meet Molly Samson, who is cleaning a pigsty. Robin introduces Molly to Mrs. Oliver, and Eve expresses interest in meeting James Bentley, suggesting that he should be invited to the dinner party.",
